Lecture : 7
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Class Base Component
Q - why do we write super(props) ?
Q -  create state variables

never update state variable directly, use below method
  this.setState({
     ount: this.state.count + 1,
     });
        
Life cycle Methods
[ https://projects.wojtekmaj.pl/react-lifecycle-methods-diagram/ ]
Q - Why componentDidMount() is use?
Q - Render Pase vs Commit Phase
Q - Why componentWillUnmount() is use?

        Loading (mounting) - first constructor is called, then render is called
  ---- mounting (cycle) ------
      Constructor (with Dummy data)
      Render (with Dummy data)
          < HTML> (NEW API data)
      ComponentDidMount()
          <API Call>
          <this.setState> -> State variable is udpated
  ---- Update cycle ------   
      render(API data)
         <HMTL> (NEW API data)
      componentDidUpdate()

      

  -- 1.With Multiple child 
  - Parent Constructor
  - Parent Render

    - First Child Constructor
    - First Child Render

    - Second Child Constructor
    - Second Child Render

    (DOM UPDATE in Single BATCH for BOTH Children)
    - First Child component Did Mount.  -> (to optimize commit Phase of first child is on HOLD )
    - Second Child component Did Mount  -> (to optimize commit Phase of first child is on HOLD )
  - Parent component Did Mount


  -- 2. With API call
  Parent Constructor
  Parent Render
    - First Child Constructor
    - First Child Render
  Parent component Did Mount
  API Call
    - First Child Render
    - First child Component Did Update
    - First Child Component Will Unmount (on chaning the current page)

